U_accept = split_self - [ alpha × max( fair_share - split_self, 0 ) + beta × max( split_self - fair_share, 0 ) ]
Summary: A fairness-based utility model for responder behavior where the utility of accepting an offer equals the offered monetary gain minus a fairness penalty. The penalty is scaled by one parameter (alpha) when the offer falls short of the contribution-based fair share and by a second parameter (beta) when the offer exceeds it.

full_reasoning:
Step-by-step reasoning:
1. Key psychological mechanisms:
 • Individuals have a fairness reference point based on their relative contribution. This can be calculated as a fair share of the combined earning based on the proportion of tokens the participant secured.
 • Deviations from this fairness benchmark lead to a reduction in the utility of accepting an offer.
 • The disutility may increase more than linearly with larger deviations; a quadratic penalty captures the idea that small imbalances are tolerated, but larger discrepancies are increasingly aversive.
 • Moreover, the psychological cost may be different when the offer is lower than the fair share (disadvantageous inequality) versus higher than the fair share (advantageous inequality).

2. Mechanism interactions:
 • The fairness benchmark is computed from tokens: F = (token_self / (token_self + token_opp)) × combined_earning.
 • When the offered split (split_self) falls below F, the loss is penalized by a sensitivity parameter γ (gamma).
 • When the offered split is above F, there is still a penalty (e.g., due to norm violations or discomfort with being “over-rewarded”), captured by another sensitivity parameter δ (delta).
 • The penalty is modeled quadratically so that the disutility is minimal for nearly fair offers and increases as the square of the deviation.

3. Mathematical form:
 • The utility for accepting an offer is:
  U_accept = split_self minus a quadratic penalty (with parameter γ if split_self < F and parameter δ if split_self ≥ F).
 • This piecewise formulation defines the utility of acceptance—each branch uses the fair share reference and the deviation between offered split and fair share.

4. Parameters:
 • γ (gamma): Learnable sensitivity to disadvantageous inequality (offer below fair share). Finite bounds, e.g., between 0 and 10.
 • δ (delta): Learnable sensitivity to advantageous inequality (offer above fair share). Finite bounds, e.g., between 0 and 10.
 • Both parameters influence the resulting utility and are intended to be recovered from the data. Their finite bounds help address potential high covariance.

5. Mapping to observable behavior:
 • The observed variable split_self (the offer the responder is given) and the tokens (token_self, token_opp) determine the fairness benchmark F.
 • The decision behavior (accept versus reject) will later be modeled probabilistically based on the computed U_accept. Here, U_accept (which can be negative or positive) directly serves as the utility indicator for accepting the offer.

Below is the formal mathematical model specification and the associated variable descriptions.

<MODEL>
Let 
 F = (token_self / (token_self + token_opp)) × combined_earning

Then, the utility for accepting an offer is defined as:
 U_accept = split_self − { γ × (F − split_self)² if split_self < F 
                δ × (split_self − F)² otherwise }
  (Represented as a piecewise function)
</MODEL>

